Interaction: Append Audit Entry

1. Spoofing of Destination Data Store Audit Log Store  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Audit Log Store may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to data being written to the attacker's target instead of Audit Log Store. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination data store.
Justification:Bitwarden uses strong cryptographic signatures, key-based authentication, and a zero-knowledge model. Data can only be written and read through authenticated service endpoints—stores cannot be impersonated.

2. Potential Excessive Resource Consumption for Secure Log Service or Audit Log Store  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:Does Secure Log Service or Audit Log Store take explicit steps to control resource consumption? Resource consumption attacks can be hard to deal with, and there are times that it makes sense to let the OS do the job. Be careful that your resource requests don't deadlock, and that they do timeout.
Justification:Bitwarden services use rate limiting, API throttling, bounded request sizes, and cloud-level protections (Azure) that enforce resource controls. Exhaustion attacks are mitigated by platform-level safeguards.

Interaction: Approval/Denial

3. Spoofing of the User External Destination Entity  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:User may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to data being sent to the attacker's target instead of User. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the external entity.
Justification:Bitwarden enforces strong authentication (email verification + master password) and supports MFA (FIDO2, authenticator app, Duo, YubiKey). MFA prevents an attacker from impersonating a user or developer.

4. External Entity User Potentially Denies Receiving Data  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:User claims that it did not receive data from a process on the other side of the trust boundary. Consider using logging or auditing to record the source, time, and summary of the received data.
Justification:All actions are logged immutably in the Bitwarden audit log with timestamps, preventing repudiation.

5. Data Flow Approval/Denial Is Potentially Interrupted  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:An external agent interrupts data flowing across a trust boundary in either direction.
Justification:All communication occurs over TLS 1.2+ with certificate pinning and integrity verification. End-to-end encryption prevents modification or injection even if traffic is intercepted.

Interaction: Approval/Waiting Period Notification

6. Spoofing the User External Entity  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:User may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to unauthorized access to Emergency Access Service. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the external entity.
Justification:Strong authentication and MFA prevent spoofing of external users.

7. Elevation Using Impersonation  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Emergency Access Service may be able to impersonate the context of User in order to gain additional privilege.
Justification:Internal process context cannot be impersonated; design prevents this.

8. Spoofing the Emergency Access Service Process  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Emergency Access Service may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to information disclosure by User. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination process.
Justification:Internal services run inside the Bitwarden infrastructure and authenticate using service-level tokens or certificates. These services do not accept unauthenticated calls.

9. Potential Lack of Input Validation for Emergency Access Service  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Data flowing across Approval/Waiting Period Notification may be tampered with by an attacker. This may lead to a denial of service attack against Emergency Access Service or an elevation of privilege attack against Emergency Access Service or an information disclosure by Emergency Access Service. Failure to verify that input is as expected is a root cause of a very large number of exploitable issues. Consider all paths and the way they handle data. Verify that all input is verified for correctness using an approved list input validation approach.
Justification:Bitwarden emergency access notifications are cryptographically authenticated and delivered via trusted channels; unauthorized modification is prevented by server-side verification

10. Potential Data Repudiation by Emergency Access Service  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:Emergency Access Service claims that it did not receive data from a source outside the trust boundary. Consider using logging or auditing to record the source, time, and summary of the received data.
Justification:All actions are logged immutably in the Bitwarden audit log with timestamps, preventing repudiation.

11. Data Flow Sniffing  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Information Disclosure
Description:Data flowing across Approval/Waiting Period Notification may be sniffed by an attacker. Depending on what type of data an attacker can read, it may be used to attack other parts of the system or simply be a disclosure of information leading to compliance violations. Consider encrypting the data flow.
Justification:All network traffic is encrypted using HTTPS/TLS, and sensitive data is additionally encrypted end-to-end.

12. Potential Process Crash or Stop for Emergency Access Service  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:Emergency Access Service crashes, halts, stops or runs slowly; in all cases violating an availability metric.
Justification:Client and server components use structured error handling, retries, and integrity checks. Vault availability is backed by encrypted server sync and redundancy on Bitwarden’s cloud infrastructure.

15. Elevation by Changing the Execution Flow in Emergency Access Service  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege

Justification:All requests require valid authentication tokens, and the service enforces server-side schema validation. Invalid or malicious inputs cannot modify execution flow.

16. Cross Site Request Forgery  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Cross-site request forgery (CSRF or XSRF) is a type of attack in which an attacker forces a user's browser to make a forged request to a vulnerable site by exploiting an existing trust relationship between the browser and the vulnerable web site. In a simple scenario, a user is logged in to web site A using a cookie as a credential. The other browses to web site B. Web site B returns a page with a hidden form that posts to web site A. Since the browser will carry the user's cookie to web site A, web site B now can take any action on web site A, for example, adding an admin to an account. The attack can be used to exploit any requests that the browser automatically authenticates, e.g. by session cookie, integrated authentication, IP whitelisting. The attack can be carried out in many ways such as by luring the victim to a site under control of the attacker, getting the user to click a link in a phishing email, or hacking a reputable web site that the victim will visit. The issue can only be resolved on the server side by requiring that all authenticated state-changing requests include an additional piece of secret payload (canary or CSRF token) which is known only to the legitimate web site and the browser and which is protected in transit through SSL/TLS. See the Forgery Protection property on the flow stencil for a list of mitigations.
Justification:Emergency contact requests only modify access state after explicit owner approval and never inject executable content. The service does not interpret any user-generated text as code.

Interaction: Audit Event

66. Cross Site Request Forgery  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Cross-site request forgery (CSRF or XSRF) is a type of attack in which an attacker forces a user's browser to make a forged request to a vulnerable site by exploiting an existing trust relationship between the browser and the vulnerable web site. In a simple scenario, a user is logged in to web site A using a cookie as a credential. The other browses to web site B. Web site B returns a page with a hidden form that posts to web site A. Since the browser will carry the user's cookie to web site A, web site B now can take any action on web site A, for example, adding an admin to an account. The attack can be used to exploit any requests that the browser automatically authenticates, e.g. by session cookie, integrated authentication, IP whitelisting. The attack can be carried out in many ways such as by luring the victim to a site under control of the attacker, getting the user to click a link in a phishing email, or hacking a reputable web site that the victim will visit. The issue can only be resolved on the server side by requiring that all authenticated state-changing requests include an additional piece of secret payload (canary or CSRF token) which is known only to the legitimate web site and the browser and which is protected in transit through SSL/TLS. See the Forgery Protection property on the flow stencil for a list of mitigations.
Justification:Bitwarden does not rely on browser cookies or implicit browser authentication for emergency access workflows. All state-changing requests require explicit, authenticated API calls using strong cryptography, not browser-automated requests. Because the Bitwarden client is not vulnerable to CSRF-style attacks, this threat is not applicable

Interaction: Secret Response

74. Potential Excessive Resource Consumption for Secrets Manager Service or Secret database  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:Does Secrets Manager Service or Secret database take explicit steps to control resource consumption? Resource consumption attacks can be hard to deal with, and there are times that it makes sense to let the OS do the job. Be careful that your resource requests don't deadlock, and that they do timeout.
Justification:Bitwarden services use rate limiting, API throttling, bounded request sizes, and cloud-level protections (Azure) that enforce resource controls. Exhaustion attacks are mitigated by platform-level safeguards.
